    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-29T10:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-29T10:41:00-05:00" n="905"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d905">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/9746</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-29T17:00:00+01:19">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 29, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.20 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2425. My 2401, April 27, 8 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d905fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    The statement which I am sending you in the following telegram was prepared by
                    the British and French Ministers. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_AH1"
                        >Allizé</persName> read it to <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1"
                        >Loudon</persName> this afternoon and left a copy with him. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> was obviously immensely
                    relieved by it. It permits of the acceptance of certain of the German demands,
                    possibly all that are essential at the moment. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TSWB1">Townley</persName> and I were present,
                    but in absence of instructions I told <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> I could not formally
                    associate myself with this statement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
